The survey of 1,000 women across the island conducted by The Carpe Diem Project and Kelly Mazur Consulting was inspired by the admission that 68 per cent of all marriages in America will end in divorce.

While research on divorce in Singapore is hard to find, committee members of the Women's Charter Scheme - which consists of counsellors, legal experts and divorce mediators - revealed that divorce is slowly becoming more common. No longer associated with social stigma, it is now viewed as an alternative to staying in a troubled marriage.

Data obtained from the Singapore Statutes show a rise in the number of divorce filings over the years.

Through the survey, participants were asked the question, "Do you think divorce is 'okay' to do?" Out of the 201 respondents, 63 per cent agreed that divorce could end a miserable relationship.

"Many women emphasised divorce is better than living unhappily under the same roof," said Ms Kelly Mazur of Kelly Ducote Mazur Consulting. "I was surprised that 40 per cent rated happiness as either 'very important' or 'almost equal' to having children."

Ms Maureen Yeoh, Chairman of The Carpe Diem Project, added that Singapore women are not as open-minded about divorce as those in the United States.
